         <abstract>
            <p>Let $R$ be the class of all functions that are properly Riemann-integrable on $\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$, and let $IR$ be the class of all functions that are properly Riemann-integrable on $\lbrack a, 1 \rbrack$ for all $a &gt; 0$ and for which $$\lim_{a \rightarrow 0} \int^1_a f(x) dx$ exists and is finite. There are computational schemes that produce a convergent sequence of approximations to the integral of any function in $R$; the trapezoid rule is one. In this paper, it is shown that there is no computational scheme that uses only evaluations of the integrand, that is similarly effective for $IR$.</p>
          </abstract>
